         <abstract>
            <p>
               Poincaré's Theorem asserts that a group $\Gamma$ of isometries of hyperbolic space $\Bbb H$ is discrete if its generators act suitably on the boundary of some polyhedron in $\Bbb H$, and when this happens a presentation of $\Gamma$ can be derived from this action. We explain methods for deducing the precise hypotheses of the theorem from calculation in $\Gamma$ when $\Gamma$ is "algorithmically defined", and we describe a file of Fortran programs that use these methods for groups $\Gamma$ acting on the upper half space model of hyperbolic 3-space $\Bbb H^3$. We exhibit one modest example of the application of these programs, and we summarize computations of representations of groups PSL$(2, \mathscr{O})$ where $\mathscr{O}$ is an order in a complex quadratic number field. 
            </p>
          </abstract>
